            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-141-person1435">
                  MICHAEL 
                  MOORE
               <interp inst="t18270913-141-person1435" type="surname" value="MOORE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-141-person1435" type="given" value="MICHAEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-141-person1435" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18270913-141-viclabel809" type="occupation">sailor</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270913-141-victim1434 t18270913-141-viclabel809"></join>, and <rs id="t18270913-141-viclabel810" type="occupation">Italian</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270913-141-victim1434 t18270913-141-viclabel810"></join>. I came here in the Saucy Jack, and have got no ship since. On the 15th of August, about eleven o'clock at night, I was in White's-yard; I met the prisoner, who took me to a house - I was very tired - I took off my jacket, and put it on a chair. I had some foreign gold and silver in the pocket - I fell on the bed, and went to sleep directly - she was then in the room. I awoke in about half an hour, and saw her over-hauling my things; I jumped out of bed, felt my pocket, and the money was gone; she put the money into her mouth; I tried to get it out, but could not. I called the watchman, who came; she then said, "I give charge of this man for ill-using me:" I said, "I give charge of this woman for robbing me;" I did not find all my money<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182709130090"></xptr>- there was 9s. 6d. taken from her mouth at the watch-house. I lost all the rest - I had not given her any thing - I was to pay her for the night's lodging certainly, but it was not agreed what. I lost one sovereign, and some Columbian money, and 9s. 6d. in silver.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-141-person1436">
                  CHRISTOPHER 
                  WARD
               <interp inst="t18270913-141-person1436" type="surname" value="WARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-141-person1436" type="given" value="CHRISTOPHER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-141-person1436" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I heard the cry of Murder! and Watch! - I went to the room, and the prisoner said, "I give charge of this man for ill-using me;" and he said, "You have got 1l. 14s. 6d. English money of mine, and if you don't give it me, he shall take you to the watch-house." I took them both to the watch-house - I saw no silver but what the prosecutor had in his hand, and which he said he got from her month - her mouth was bleeding - they were quarrelling together.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-141-person1437">
                  JOHN 
                  DANGATE
               <interp inst="t18270913-141-person1437" type="surname" value="DANGATE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-141-person1437" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-141-person1437" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was the watch-house keeper. The prisoner was brought to me, and the prosecutor accused her of robbing him of 14s. 6d., one sovereign, two quarter-dollars, and one half-dollar - the prisoner said she had not got any thing upon her person. I searched her, and found in the left side of her mouth (which was bleeding) 9s. 6d. in silver, and there was sixpenny worth of copper in her hand; this half-dollar, and two quarter-dollars, the prosecutor gave me, and told me he took them out of her left hand.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. When he got up into the room he asked me for a light, and said he thought he had lost some money - he pulled out a 5l. note, and said, "Some of those girls in the public-house have robbed me;" I said, "Recollect you have not lost it here;" and then he sent me for something to drink, and gave me 6s. I did not rob him - he was asleep above an hour; and if I had been disposed to rob him, I should have taken all his money.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18270913-141-verdict811" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18270913-141-verdict811" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 23.</p>
